Files:
- platform/mcp-server/src/adapter-files.ts (IIFE wrapper generation)
- platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/execute-script.ts (passes execId, may need to pass startedKey)

Context:
The IIFE wrapper is generated in `writeExecFile` (adapter-files.ts lines 177-197). The current wrapper:
```js
(function() {
  var __ot = globalThis.__openTabs = globalThis.__openTabs || {};
  var __resultKey = "__execResult_<uuid>";
  var __asyncKey = "__execAsync_<uuid>";
  try {
    var __r = (async function() { <user-code> })();
    // ... async detection and .then() chaining
  } catch (e) { ... }
})();
```

Changes:
Add a `__startedKey` variable and set it immediately after `__ot` initialization:
```js
(function() {
  var __ot = globalThis.__openTabs = globalThis.__openTabs || {};
  var __resultKey = "__execResult_<uuid>";
  var __asyncKey = "__execAsync_<uuid>";
  var __startedKey = "__execStarted_<uuid>";
  __ot[__startedKey] = true;
  try {
    // ... existing code unchanged
  } catch (e) { ... }
})();
```

The startedKey variable name should be derived from the same `execId` UUID used for resultKey and asyncKey. Currently `resultKey` = `__execResult_${execId}` and `asyncKey` = `__execAsync_${execId}`. Add `startedKey` = `__execStarted_${execId}`.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the existing result/async key logic
- Do NOT change how user code is wrapped
- The started flag MUST be set synchronously at the top of the IIFE before the try block

Files:
- e2e/browser-tools.e2e.ts (E2E tests, no changes needed — just run them)

Context:
The flaky test is at line 852:
```ts
test('await fetch returns HTTP status', async ({ mcpServer, testServer, extensionContext: _extensionContext, mcpClient }) => {
  await initAndListTools(mcpServer, mcpClient);
  const tabId = await openTestServerTab(mcpClient, testServer);
  const result = await mcpClient.callTool('browser_execute_script', {
    tabId,
    code: 'const r = await fetch(window.location.href); return r.status',
  });
  expect(result.isError).toBe(false);
  const data = parseToolResult(result.content);
  const value = data.value as Record<string, unknown>;
  expect(value.value).toBe(200);
  await mcpClient.callTool('browser_close_tab', { tabId });
});
```

The failure was: Expected 200, Received undefined. This happened because the polling function returned { error: 'No result captured' } before the IIFE had executed. With the started sentinel fix, the polling function will return { pending: true } until the IIFE begins, then correctly wait for the async result.

Run: `npm run test:e2e`

Do NOT modify any test files. The existing tests should pass as-is with the infrastructure fix.

Constraints:
- Do NOT add retries to the Playwright config — the fix should eliminate the flakiness, not mask it
- Do NOT modify any test expectations or test code
- If any test fails, investigate whether the started sentinel logic has a bug, not the test
